post_text: Great reminder!
shared_text:
Mindful Moments Preschool & Before/After School Care
April 20 at 9:43 AM Â·

Look at the differences between a typical younger childâ€™s hand (left) and a typical older child's hand (right). I have parents asking regularly why their preschool aged child isnâ€™t able to write yet. This is why! Their hands (and brains) are still developing and are not fully formed. So what should they be doing to support this? PLAY!! Playdough, colouring, cutting, gluing, playing outside, digging in dirt, sensory play, dress up play, science experiments, beading, puzzles, throwing balls, etc. All of these things help their hands develop. When they are physically ready to write, they will! No need to rush them, they will show you when they are ready!

I â¤ï¸ puppets!

For young children who avert eye gaze during therapy sessions, holding a puppet next to my face is usually a game changer!

The puppet can point to pictures in books, or help put toys away, or watch my mouth when I say words.

In essence, the puppet becomes the model for the child ğŸ§’ğŸ½ğŸ‘¶ğŸ¼ğŸ‘¦ğŸ»

I have a wide variety of puppets at my disposal. For kiddos with suspected CAS, I love using a cute oven mitt as a puppet. Why, you ask. Because an oven mitt is like a giant mouth and it shows jaw movement.

I also like adding puppets to story time to keep the young childâ€™s focus and attention on me and the book. I have collected a variety of finger puppets to pair with different books.

During an international pandemic, it is important to add that puppets can be used effectively during Teletherapy sessions too!

Who else uses puppets to support play-based learning? Reply with a â¤ï¸ if you love puppets too!

shared_text:
Food Bank for the Heartland
June 22 at 1:07 PM Â·

If your child was on free or reduced lunch in Nebraska this last school year, you may be eligible for Pandemic EBT funds (similar to food stamps). Up to $281 per child. This program is not based on income, only on your child's free or reduced lunch status. Call the SNAP outreach hotline at 1-855-444-5556 today. It only takes 5 minutes to apply. Please have your child's student ID ready.

If you already receive SNAP benefits, you do not need to apply because you will automatically be enrolled. Please apply if you do not currently receive SNAP benefits.

post_text: There is still time to register for preschool!
shared_text:
Jefferson Elementary
June 4 at 9:14 AM Â·

Do you have a child who will be 4 before July 31st of this year? The North Platte Public School's Bullpup Preschools still have openings for the 20-21 school year. We have full-day openings left at the Buffalo Early Learning Center, and we have half-day openings at Osgood Elementary in the afternoons and Jefferson Elementary for both the morning and afternoon sections. Spots are limited, and they will fill up fast, so please register today!

For more information see our website at https://www.nppsd.org/vnews/display.v/SEC/Preschool

To register go to https://www.nppsd.org/vnews/display.v/SEC/Students%20&%20Parents%7cNew%20Student%20Registration

post_text: Check out this new tool to help you find childcare centers near you!
shared_text:
Buffett Early Childhood Institute
April 20 at 3:14 PM Â·

Good news: A group of early childhood organizations have collaborated to create the Nebraska Child Care Referral Network â€” a searchable child care database for parents and providers at
www.nechildcarereferral.org.
Many of our friends and neighbors must still report to jobs outside their homes during the COVID-19 crisis. This website can help those who need quality emergency child care find it.
Why is this important?
â€¢ Many states already have a child care resource and referral website, so this is historic for Nebraska.
â€¢ This is a response to what families and providers are telling us they need
â€¢ Child care providers are an essential, but often overlooked, part of our communities
â€¢ This database will live on beyond COVID-19 emergency, connecting families who need quality child care with the provider that's right for them.
Thank you to Nebraska Children and Families Foundation for leading this charge and to every statewide partner who helped make it a reality.

shared_text:
The OT Toolbox
April 18 at 9:40 AM Â·

We all experience reactions to stress from time to time, however, when a child is experiencing child traumatic stress, these reactions may interfere with his or her daily life and ability to function and interact with others. Stress can look like different things in kiddos. Establishing routines is one strategy to give a child a sense of normalcy. Here are tips to help in establishing new routines.

Pdf available here: https://www.shrs.pitt.edu/ot/covid-19-tips/children-and-family-resources

post_text: We are missing our providers in the office, but look at the fun things they are doing at home. Jade is correct, PLAY is so IMPORTANT! Check out the ideas Jade has to share in her post.
shared_text:
Jade Hodson Siegel
March 23 at 10:10 PM Â·

Yes I'm still on my soapbox about PLAY!

Redmond is our judgemental, opinionated, middle child who has ZERO interest in sitting and doing "school stuff." And to be honest, it would be developmentally INAPPROPRIATE to expect that of him.

Well here are a few of the language and learning concepts we "worked" on while building his "vacuum cleaner":

Size comparison- tall/taller/short/shorter/long/longer

Colors- red, yellow, blue

Descriptive vocabulary- fast/slow, round, rolling, push/pull, in/on/off, together/apart, same/match/different, broken/fixed

He had to problem solve a way to negotiate a trade with his brother to get the pieces he needed to make it "roll right"

He had to PERSIST through several breaks (as you can see in the picture)

So if you want some extra tips for young kiddos at home right now...LET THEM PLAY. It is absolutely the most meaningful way kids learn!

shared_text:
National Center for Pyramid Model Innovations
March 20 at 10:16 AM Â·

New #PyramidModel Resource for Emotional Regulation AT HOME!

"Tucker Turtle Takes Time to Tuck and Think at Home"

Tucker the Turtle provides a scripted story to teach young children how to calm down when they have strong feelings by tucking into their shell and taking deep breaths. The story also includes visuals to help children learn how to use the strategy.

Available in our resource library
https://challengingbehavior.cbcs.usf.edu/resources/index.html

and our new Emergency and Disaster page.
https://challengingbehavior.org/emergency

Spanish available.

post_text: Tummy time, is important time!
shared_text:
The OT Toolbox
February 28 at 12:44 PM Â·

ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼

WHAT EVERY OT WISHES EVERY PARENT KNEW

Development, strength and milestones happens on the floor!â â €
â â €
Tummy time helps build so many muscles, sensory outputs and skills that they will need to get to the next milestones in their motor development journey.â â €
â â €
Don't skip this step - it's the foundation for everything!â â €
â â €
Tummy time helps build:â â €
âœ¨Balance (vestibular sense)â â €
âœ¨Neck & back musclesâ â €
âœ¨Visual trackingâ â €
âœ¨Arm & wrist strengthâ â €
âœ¨Core strengthâ â €
âœ¨Flexor musclesâ â €
âœ¨Spinal strengthâ â €

Julie Geiser
July 31, 2019 at 11:37 AM Â·

Family fishing night

A Family Fishing Event will be held on Friday, Aug. 2 at Iron Horse Lake in North Platte. Times are 6 p.m. to 8 p.m.

Family Fishing is a Nebraska Game and Parks program designed to help make family fishing adventures possible and rewarding. The event is free and loaner fishing equipment, bait and staff will be on hand to assist those of all ages learn the basics of this fun and relaxing activity. Everyone is invited regardless of age or skill. Those 16 years and older wanting to fish will need a valid fishing license.

Look for the colorful fishing trailer at the west end of Iron Horse Lake. Iron Horse is located at the intersection of Interstate 80 and Highway 83 next to the Veteranâ€™s Memorial.

Parents and Guardians of 2019-2020 Kindergarten Students (Children who will be 5 years of no later than July 31st.) Here is some important information to note:

If you have not registered your child to attend kindergarten this fall, please complete the online registration form as soon as possible at: http://www.nppsd.org/vnews/display.v/SEC/New%20Student%20Registration.

If your child is currently enrolled in North Platte Public Schools Preschools, there is no need to complete the registration form as your student's enrollment will roll to Kindergarten at your resident boundary school.

The date for Kindergarten Roundup is April 16th at 5:30 for all elementary schools. Please note that Osgood is the attendance site for Kindergarten students living in the Lake Maloney/Osgood boundaries.

Make It Less Stressful for Children with Autism to Return to School

Autism Society Nebraska
August 3, 2018 at 9:34 AM Â·

"If you're a parent of a child with autism, you are aware that they are very much into their routines, so new places and new things can be very difficult. Taking them early so that they can get comfortable with the environment, with the school classroom, so that they can meet the teacher and so they can understand a little more what is going to happen. Make sure that they are comfortable in that environment."

https://healthcare.utah.edu/the-scope/shows.php?shows=0_ovbdxr9h

shared_text:
Julie Geiser
June 14, 2018 at 2:46 PM Â·

Family fishing night

The Nebraska Game and Parks Commission will be hosting a family fishing night on Friday, June 22 at Birdwood Lake Wildlife Management Area from 6 p.m. to 8 p.m.

Family fishing nights are a Nebraska Game and Parks program designed to help make family fishing adventures possible and rewarding. The events are free and loaner fishing equipment, bait and staff will be on hand to assist those of all ages learn the basics of this fun and relaxing activity. Everyone is invited regardless of age or skill. Those 16 years and older wanting to fish will need a valid fishing license.

Look for the colorful fishing trailer at the lake. Birdwood is referred to as Fire Lake by some and is the first I80 Lake west of North Platte. To get to the lake, take Walker Road west then north on Homestead Road.
